definitions.definition: True , genuine , not merely nominal or apparent .
examples: City hall has its place, but this pub is the real heart of the town.

definitions.definition: Genuine , not artificial , counterfeit , or fake .
Actually being , existing , or occurring ; not fictitious or imaginary .

examples: No one has ever seen a real unicorn.

definitions.definition: Having been adjusted to remove the effects of inflation ; measured in purchasing power ( contrast nominal ) .
examples: My dad calculated my family's real consumption per month.
What is the real GNP of this polity?

definitions.definition: Relating to the result of the actions of rational agents; relating to neoclassical economic models as opposed to Keynesian models.
Being either a rational number, or the limit of a convergent infinite sequence of rational numbers: being one of a set of numbers with a one-to-one correspondence to the points on a line.
Signifying meritorious qualities or actions , especially with regard to genuineness , groundedness , and true success rather than poser imitations of success.

subdefinitions.definition: Firm through directness , readiness to confront.
examples: yo, Imma be real with u... don't ever text me again
